      <Abstract xml:lang="en">Stochastic optimal control theory (SOC) considers the problem to compute an optimal sequence of actions to attain a future goal. Solving this for high dimensional systems is difficult in general. Path integral (PI) control problems (Kappen 2005) represent a large class of non-linear control problems for which the optimal control and the optimal cost-to-go can be expressed in closed form as a Feyman- Kac path integral. As a result, the optimal control can be estimated using Monte Carlo sampling. The path integral control methods has been applied with great success in robotics by various leading robotics research groups world wide. The MC sampling can be significantly accelerated using importance sampling (IS), It can be shown that better controllers, in the sense of control cost, are better importance samplers, in terms of sampling efficiency. This allows the design of adaptive importance samplers using self-generated data. Arbitrary control precision can be achieved by increasing the data size and the model complexity, such as for instance deep neural networks. This approach scales to very large control problems, much larger than can be currently solved using the Bellman equation PDE. The long term vision is to build a computer infrastructure that computes a controller for any user specified control problem. This pilot project will provide the first step to parallelize this computation and to assess the scalability of this approach for large complex control problems. Specifically, we aim to demonstrate improved solutions to three control problems in three neuroscience and robotics applications.</Abstract>
